  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT238-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">talaimakaḷ parattaiyiṉ maṟuttantu vāyil vēṇṭit tōḻiyiṭaic ceṉṟu teḷippāṉ
          pukkāṟkut (G2: pukkāṟṟit) tōḻi colliyatu,</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to the one who entered in
          order to explain, having gone to the confidante wishing for the door/mediation, after HE
          had been brought back from the other woman/courtesan. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT238">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> pācava liṭitta karuṅkā ḻulakkai</l>
          <l> yāykatir nelliṉ varampaṇait tuyiṟṟi</l>
          <l> yoṇṭoṭi makaḷir vaṇṭa layarun</l>
          <l> toṇṭi yaṉṉaveṉ ṉalantantu</l>
          <l> koṇṭaṉai ceṉmō makiḻnaniṉ cūḷē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Having given [back] my innocence, [which is] like Toṇṭi,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">where women with bright bracelets are engaged in play,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">having laid down on a ridge by the border</l>
          <l rend="indent7">of the rice field with choice ears</l>
          <l rend="indent3">the black, hard pestles which pounded green rice, <note place="foot">Meaning
            (and impact) as well as the precise construction of the lines 1-3 are quite unclear.
            T.V.G.'s explanation is that the region of Toṇṭi is so fertile that the women do not
            need to work too much, but are able to rest and play when the work is done.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent">– [since] you have taken [back] your oath, delightful man, go!</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="4+5b">
            <l>[Since you have] given [back] my innocence ...,</l>
            <l>take [back] your oath, delightful man, [and] go!</l>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
